Persistent dispatch for Q2_K down kernel

STATUS: open. Untested follow-up to the gate_up persistent+LDS-grid win
(commit ff4aec4) which gave +7% on the gate_up half of routed_moe.

CONTEXT: rocm_moe_down_q2k_wmma_kernel is the larger half of the
routed_moe wall fraction.  Current profile (184-tok prefill,
DS4_ROCM_SYNC_EACH=1):
  routed_moe_batch total:  59.6% wall (1.513 s / 2.539 s)
  gate_up (optimized):    ~22% wall (post-session)
  down (untouched):       ~27% wall (per feedback_moe_wmma_at_memunit_ceiling.md
                                     down is the larger contributor)

Down is launched as a 2D grid (dn_row_blocks x n_unique_experts).  No
persistent variant exists today.  Gate_up's persistent+LDS-grid won by
amortizing the 2 KiB LDS-grid staging across 320 grid-stride blocks
instead of ~32K (e, row_block) tiles.  Down has no LUT to stage so the
same amortization doesn't apply directly, BUT persistent grouping may
still help by keeping per-expert weight rows L2-warm across all its
row_blocks before moving to the next expert.

GOAL: positive prefill delta from a persistent down kernel, validated
on the 184-tok canonical bench.  Threshold to land: >= +1.5% prefill.

NEXT STEPS:
1. Add rocm_moe_down_q2k_wmma_persistent_kernel.  Mirror the existing
   rocm_moe_gate_up_iq2xxs_wmma_persistent_kernel structure: grid
   (N_PERSIST, 1, 1) with grid-stride over (e_dense, row_block) tiles
   in expert-major order.  Same per-tile body as the non-persistent
   down kernel.
2. Env-gate via a new DS4_ROCM_MOE_DOWN_PERSISTENT (or share
   DS4_ROCM_MOE_PERSISTENT and gate both at once).  N_PERSIST default
   320 to match gate_up.
3. Wire dispatch in the same site as gate_up persistent (~ds4_rocm.c
   line 9940-ish, after the gate_up persistent branch).  Down is
   launched after gate_up so persistent down can follow immediately.
4. Bench: 184-tok long_prompt, --temp 0 --seed 42, 3 runs each:
   - Default (persistent gate_up only)
   - +Persistent down enabled
   Compare medians.
5. If positive, also sweep N_PERSIST for the down kernel separately
   (the optimum may differ from gate_up's 320 since down has different
   per-tile work).

VALIDATION GATES:
- DS4_ROCM=1 make ds4 ds4_rocm_kernel_test
- ./ds4_rocm_kernel_test (40 tests OK)
- Validation prompt -n 200 --temp 0 --seed 42: coherent thinking-mode reply
- Bench above

RISKS:
- Persistent down may regress like persistent gate_up did pre-LDS-grid
  (-1.7..-2.7%).  The gate_up regression was caused by HIP's native
  scheduler clustering tiles better than grid-stride.  Down has the
  same characteristics, so a regression is plausible.
- Activations (mid[] = 9 MB at n_tokens=184, n_used=6, mid_dim=2048)
  fit in 32 MB Infinity Cache anyway; locality benefit may be marginal.

UPPER BOUND: optimistic ~5% wall improvement if expert-major locality
gives a 20% kernel speedup; realistic 0-2% wall.

